WHEREAS, since the passing of his father, Mr. McDonald has continued to evolve the
farm to keep pace with market needs, such as moving away from dairy to focus on other
commodities, and he has a forward-facing vision that always seeks to incorporate cutting-edge
agricultural technology for the good of the environment and the consumer; and
WHEREAS, distinctive in his consistent excellence, Mr. McDonald was honored in 1990
as Young Farmer of the Year, and capitalizing on his vast experience, he has served the
agricultural industry at the county, state, and national level, being a member of the Smith
County Farm Bureau and having held seats on the Smith Farmers Co-Op Board of Directors,
Tennessee Corn Promotion Board, North American Strawberry Growers Association, and
Tennessee Farm Bureau State Board of Directors; and
WHEREAS, it is Mr. McDonald's pride and joy to be able to farm alongside his daughter,
Sarah; his mother, Linda; Kyle Cato; and more than forty full-time and part-time employees and
contract workers; and
WHEREAS, Mr. McDonald was nominated for this prestigious honor by Katie Martin,
agriculture agent and director of UT Extension Smith County, who praised him as a smart
businessman, a passionate agriculturist, and an integral part of his community, and applauded
his outstanding advocacy for the farming industry, his commitment to efficiency, sustainability,
and diversification, and his allegiance to his employees, whom he treats like family; and
WHEREAS, George McDonald exemplifies the spirit and dedication that are
characteristic of a true Tennessean, and we find it appropriate to honor and commend such an
outstanding and remarkable individual; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor and congratulate George McDonald of Smith County upon his
